1.name: same-sex marriage equality
1.description: the Federal Government should amend the Marriage Act 1961 so that same-sex couples can marry under Australian law

2.name: tobacco plain packaging
2.description: the federal government should introduce plain packaging for tobacco products

3.name: a carbon price
3.description: the federal government should introduce a carbon pricing mechanism

4.name: increasing scrutiny of asylum seeker management
4.description: there should be more independent access to detention centres and more information provided about the management of asylum seekers under Australian government policy, including the interception of boats at sea

5.name: government administered paid parental leave
5.description: the federal government should administer the paid parental leave scheme rather than employers

6.name: increasing trade unions' powers in the workplace
6.description: the federal government should introduce legislation that increases the powers and influence of trade unions in workplace relations

7.name: the Carbon Pollution Reduction Scheme
7.description: the federal government should introduce the Carbon Pollution Reduction Scheme, which is a cap-and-trade system of emissions trading introduced by the Rudd Labor Government

8.name: implementing refugee and protection conventions
8.description: the federal government should implement the international conventions that relate to seeking refuge and protection from torture. These include the Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, the Protocol relating to the Status of Refugees and the non-refoulement provisions of the UN Convention Against Torture and the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights

9.name: increasing competition in bulk wheat export
9.description: the federal government should deregulate Australia's wheat export market so that bulk wheat export is no longer done through a single exporter (which is known as a 'single desk' policy)

10.name: recognising local government in the Constitution
10.description: local government should be recognised in the Australian Constitution

11.name: temporary protection visas
11.description: the Federal government should introduce temporary protection visas

12.name: voluntary student union fees
12.description: university students should be able to choose whether or not to pay student services and amenities fees (also called student union fees)

13.name: increasing or removing the Government debt limit
13.description: the federal government should increase the limit on the total amount of Commonwealth stock and securities that may be on issue at any time (known as the 'debt limit') or remove the limit altogether

14.name: a minerals resource rent tax
14.description: the federal government should put a tax on profits earned from mining mineral resources such as coal and iron ore

15.name: increasing protection of Australia's fresh water
15.description: the federal government should introduce legislation that increases the protection of Australia's fresh water resources, including its river and groundwater systems

16.name: regional processing of asylum seekers
16.description: asylum seekers who arrive in Australia without a visa, particularly those who arrive by boat, should have their asylum claims processed regionally in a country such as the Republic of Nauru or Papua New Guinea (See the policy "For offshore processing of asylum seekers" for more on processing asylum seeker claims in Australian territories like Christmas Island)

17.name: increasing marine conservation
17.description: the federal government should introduce legislation and regulations that protect and conserve Australia's marine ecosystems such as the Great Barrier Reef

18.name: unconventional gas mining
18.description: the federal government should allow companies to mine coal seam (CSG), tight and shale gas

19.name: restricting foreign ownership
19.description: the federal government should restrict foreign ownership within Australia, particularly where foreign ownership would be against the national interest

20.name: increasing investment in renewable energy
20.description: the federal government should increase investment in renewable energy technologies

21.name: privatising government assets
21.description: the federal government should privatise government owned assets

22.name: stem cell research
22.description: the federal government should allow certain types of stem cell research, including human embryo research

23.name: more scrutiny of intelligence services & police
23.description: there should be more scrutiny or oversight of the actions and powers of Australian intelligence and law enforcement agencies, including the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (ASIO), the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (ASIS) and the Australian Federal Police (AFP)

24.name: increasing Aboriginal land rights
24.description: the federal government should increase Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander land rights by, for example, increasing their legal recognition and protection

25.name: increasing funding for university education
25.description: the federal government should increase funding for university education

26.name: decreasing the private health insurance rebate
26.description: the federal government should decrease the private health insurance rebate that eligible taxpayers are entitled to

27.name: increasing the price of subsidised medicine
27.description: the federal government should increase the amount that patients pay for medicine under the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (PBS) and the Repatriation Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (known as the 'co-payment')

28.name: increasing the age pension
28.description: the federal government should increase the amount of the age pension

29.name: extending government benefits to same-sex couples
29.description: the federal government should extend any financial and work-related entitlements and benefits that currently only apply to heterosexual couples to same-sex couples and their children

30.name: increasing protection of Aboriginal heritage sites
30.description: the federal government should increase the protection of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander cultural heritage sites

31.name: increasing availability of abortion drugs
31.description: the federal government should increase the availability of RU486 and other medications that can induce an abortion

32.name: live animal export
32.description: the federal government should allow live animal export and place minimal restrictions on it

33.name: carbon farming
33.description: the federal government should introduce a carbon farming initiative that encourages the farming and timber industries to decrease carbon emissions or to increase carbon storage (known as carbon sequestration)

34.name: decreasing availability of welfare payments
34.description: the federal government should limit the availability of government social security payments

35.name: re-approving/ re-registering agvet chemicals
35.description: the federal government should, in relation to agricultural and veterinary ('agvet') chemicals, implement a mandatory scheme for the re-approval of active constituents and re-registration of chemical products to ensure their ongoing safety

36.name: the Intervention in the Northern Territory
36.description: the Federal Government should respond to reports about high levels of child sexual abuse in some Indigenous communities in the Northern Territory by introducing the Northern Territory National Emergency Response or the very similar Stronger Futures Policy, also referred to as "the intervention"

37.name: an emissions reduction fund
37.description: the federal government should introduce an emissions reduction fund so it can buy domestic greenhouse gas emissions reductions and offsets by reverse auction. This is a key part of the Coalition Government's Direct Action policy.

38.name: increasing funding for road infrastructure
38.description: the federal government should provide more funding for road infrastructure

39.name: increasing restrictions on gambling
39.description: the federal government should increase restrictions on the gambling industry in order to address the issue of problem gambling

40.name: increasing beef import standards
40.description: the federal government should increase the standards and assessment processes that protect the public and beef industry from diseases such as mad cow disease

41.name: increasing fishing restrictions
41.description: the federal government should increase fishing restrictions so that fish populations are sustainable

42.name: encouraging Australian-based industry
42.description: the federal government should encourage Australian-based industry and secure the jobs these industries create by, for example, providing incentives for companies to stay in Australia (note that there are specific policies in respect to the timber, dairy, shipping, coal, and film & TV industries so votes on those subjects are not included here)

43.name: uranium export
43.description: the federal government should support the exportation of uranium from Australia

44.name: increasing surveillance powers
44.description: the federal government should introduce legislation to increase the powers of intelligence and law enforcement agencies to intercept and retain communications related to persons of interest. These agencies include the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (ASIO), Australian Secret Intelligence Service (ASIS) and the Australian Federal Police (AFP).

45.name: increasing consumer protections
45.description: the federal government should introduce legislation that increases consumer protections by, for example, encouraging competition

46.name: increasing access under Freedom of Information law
46.description: the federal government should amend freedom of information (FOI) legislation to increase public access to government data and documents

47.name: an NBN (using fibre to the premises)
47.description: the federal government should introduce a National Broadband Network ('NBN') using the fibre to the premises ('FTTP') design

50.name: a federal inquiry into Queensland government administration
50.description: the federal government should establish a Select Committee on Certain Aspects of Queensland Government Administration related to Commonwealth Government Affairs

51.name: offshore processing for people seeking asylum in Australia
51.description: people seeking asylum in Australia, who arrive without a visa and particularly those who arrive by boat, should be held offshore in an Australian territory like Christmas Island while their application is processed (See the policy "For regional processing of asylum seekers" for more on processing asylum claims in other countries, like Nauru)

53.name: increasing freedom of political communication
53.description: the federal government should increase freedom of political communication in Australia by, for example, protecting people's right to inform others about issues and events in the public interest

54.name: storing all citizens' telecommunications data for access by government agencies
54.description: telecommunications providers should be required to store all their customers' usages data for later access by agencies with the Attorney General's consent

55.name: requiring a warrant to access citizens telecommunications records
55.description: staff of government agencies should need a warrant before being able to access the telecommunications records of citizens

56.name: decreasing ABC and SBS funding
56.description: the federal government should decrease funding for the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) and the Special Broadcasting Service (SBS)

57.name: tighter means testing of family payments
57.description: the federal government should target family payments to low and moderate income households, to the exclusion of higher income households.

58.name: deregulating undergraduate university fees
58.description: the federal government should remove limits on the amount that universities can charge students for tuition in Commonwealth Supported Places (CSPs)

59.name: increasing accessibility of government data and documents
59.description: The federal government should make its data and documents more accessible for the general public and Parliament

60.name: removing children from immigration detention
60.description: the federal government should not put asylum seeker children into immigration detention and should release all children now in detention

61.name: funding the national school chaplaincy program
61.description: The federal government should continue to fund the National School Chaplaincy Program (NSCP) to fund chaplains in Australian primary and secondary schools

62.name: landholders' right to say no to mining and gas exploration
62.description: landholders, particularly farmers, should be able to say no to mining and gas exploration on their land (in other words, they should be able to lock the gate)

63.name: building Australias new submarine fleet in South Australia
63.description: the federal government should make sure that a planned fleet of 12 new submarines is built in South Australia (this new fleet was proposed in 2013 to replace the existing Collins Class submarine fleet)

65.name: compensating victims of overseas terrorism since the September 11 attack
65.description: the federal government should extend compensation to all Australian victims of overseas terrorism since the 11 September 2001 attack, or to their next of kin

66.name: giving apprentices access to a $20,000 loan
66.description: the federal government should introduce a loan program for apprentices, to a maximum of $20,000, like the program currently available for university students

67.name: protecting whales within Australian waters
67.description: the Federal Government should protect whales within Australian waters by, for example, taking action against the Japanese Government over its whaling program in the Southern Ocean

68.name: increasing the diversity of media ownership
68.description: the federal government should use regulation to increase the diversity of publishers and broadcasters in Australia's media industry by, for example, setting a threshold for the maximum market share of any one company.

69.name: increasing support for community radio and TV
69.description: the federal government should support community broadcasting (radio and television) by, for example, increasing its funding and its ability to broadcast

70.name: increasing indexation of HECS-HELP debts
70.description: Higher Education Loan Programme (HELP) debts - also known as HECS-HELP debts - should be indexed in line with the ten-year bond rate, capped at six per cent, instead of the generally lower rate of the Consumer Price Index (CPI)

71.name: charging postgraduate research students fees
71.description: the federal government should let universities charge postgraduate research students fees

72.name: decreasing the gender pay gap
72.description: the federal government should introduce legislation that reduces the gap in income between women and men and ensures both sexes are paid equally well

73.name: greater public scrutiny of the Trans-Pacific Partnership negotiations
73.description: the Australian Government should publicly release more information about the contents of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) trade deal and its position in the negotiations

75.name: increasing transparency of the China-Australia relationship
75.description: the Australian Government should provide more transparency of our country's political relationship with China

77.name: the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) Agreement
77.description: the federal government should support Australia joining the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) Agreement, a trade agreement between countries along the rim of the Pacific Ocean, including Canada and New Zealand

78.name: requiring Parliamentary approval of military deployments
78.description: Australia should not deploy armed forces without the consideration and approval of Parliament

79.name: Government direct and indirect action on climate change as a matter of urgency
79.description: the AU Government must address the causes and consequences of climate change as a matter of urgency with explicit proactive policies and direct & indirect actions

80.name: Speaker of the House of Representatives, Bronwyn Bishop
80.description: the Speaker has the confidence of the house and your support to remain in the position.

81.name: increasing transparency of big business by making information public
81.description: the federal govenment should increase transparency in big business (that is, companies with an income equal or more than $100 million/year or, alternatively, $200 million/year) by making certain information public, including their total income and how much tax they paid

82.name: making Australians working overseas repay their student debts
82.description: the Federal Government should make Australians working overseas repay their Higher Education Loan Programme debts (known as HELP or HECS debts) and their Trade Support Loan debts (known as TSL debts) under the same compulsory repayment system that applies to citizens working in Australia

83.name: letting environmental groups challenge the legality of certain government decisions
83.description: environmental and conservation groups should be able to challenge the legality of federal government decisions made under the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 (EPBC Act) (in other words, they should have standing to seek judicial review under that Act)

84.name: revoking citizenship of dual nationals involved with terrorism offences by the minister
84.description: the federal government should give the immigration minister the power to revoke the citizenship of people who have dual nationality (that is, are also citizens of another country) if they take part in certain terrorism-related offences

85.name: restricting donations to political parties
85.description: the federal government should introduce restrictions to the amount and type of donations that political parties can receive in order to prevent corruption or the appearance of corruption in government

86.name: creating a federal Anti-Corruption Commission
86.description: the federal government should create a national integrity commission similar to the NSW Independent Commission Against Corruption (ICAC) to detect, investigate and prevent corruption across all Commonwealth departments and agencies

87.name: withdrawing troops from Afghanistan
87.description: the federal government should begin to withdraw Australian troops from Afghanistan as soon as safely possible

88.name: using natural resource wealth for the benefit of all Australians
88.description: the federal government should use the wealth generated by mining for the benefit of Australian citizens, as encouraged by the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative (EITI) Principles

89.name: Senate electoral reform
89.description: the federal government should change the laws governing Senate elections to allow voters more direct control over the flow of preferences, whether they vote above or below the line

90.name: protecting whistleblowers
90.description: the federal government should introduce legislation to protect people who disclose information for the benefit of the public interest

91.name: a fast transition from fossil fuels to renewable energy
91.description: in light of the threat of climate change, the federal government should make as rapid a transition to renewable energy as possible

92.name: stopping tax avoidance or aggressive tax minimisation
92.description: the federal government should make it harder for individuals and corporations to avoid or aggressively minimise their Australian tax obligations and take part in international efforts to keep track of these individuals and corporations by sharing income and asset information

93.name: ending illegal logging
93.description: the federal government should introduce legislation to end illegal logging and prevent the importation of timber that has been illegally harvested.

94.name: protecting threatened forest and bushland habitats
94.description: the federal government should protect threatened forest and bushland habitats from logging.

95.name: a Royal Commission into banking
95.description: the federal government should establish a Royal Commission into misconduct within the banking and financial services sector.

96.name: a review of parliamentary entitlements
96.description: the federal government should set up a review of parliamentary entitlements and allowances, including legitimate expenditure, salary packages, superannuation entitlements and other allowances

97.name: the use of strong encryption technologies
97.description:
Strong encryption technologies are critical and necessary enablers of communications and commerce.
Strong encryption technologies should not be restricted, back-doored, undermined or crippled by law.

98.name: increasing parliamentary entitlements for current MPs and Senators
98.description: the federal governmnet should increase parliamentary entitlements for current MPs and Senators, such as legitimate expenditure, salary packages, superannuation entitlements and/or other allowances like the printing allowance

99.name: increasing the foreign aid budget to 0.7% of Gross National Income
99.description: the federal government should allocate 0.7% of Gross National Income (GNI) to foreign aid in line with the United Nations' target

100.name: Copyright reforms
100.description: Copyright laws in Australia requires reforms to modernise the Copyright Act, as recommended by the The Australian Law Reform Commission (ALRC). Australia should broaden the existing 'fair dealing' exceptions to a much broader, flexible 'fair use' exception, in line with US copyright law.

101.name: removing parallel import restrictions for books
101.description: the federal government should remove the current parallel import restrictions on books (also known as territorial copyright protections) so that an Australian territorial rights holder of a particular book cannot prevent others from importing that book from outside Australia at potentially lower prices

102.name: local community consultation on infrastructure projects
102.description: the federal government should always consult with local communities that may be affected by infrastructure projects, especially for major infrastructure projects such as dams, pulp mills or nuclear facilities

103.name: a plebiscite on the carbon pricing mechanism
103.description: the federal government should hold a plebiscite to gauge whether citizens support or oppose introducing a carbon pricing mechanism (also known as a 'carbon tax')

104.name: maintaining or increasing CSIRO funding
104.description: the federal government should maintain or increase the amount of funding allocated to the Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO)

105.name: increasing funding for legal aid
105.description: the federal government should maintain or increase funding for the legal assistance sector (Legal Aid, community legal centres, etc.)

107.name: buffer zones around abortion clinics
107.description: protests shouldn't be allowed close to abortion clinics

108.name: time-based restrictions on alcohol sales and venue entry
108.description: venues shouldn't be allowed to accept new customers and alcohol sales should be forbidden after specified times

109.name: putting welfare payments onto cashless debit cards (or indue cards) on a temporary basis as a trial
109.description: the federal government should create a time-limited trial of putting a large proportion of a person's welfare payment onto a debit card that cannot be used for alcohol or gambling and cannot be used to make cash withdrawals (see the policy "For putting welfare payments onto cashless debit cards (or indue cards) on an ongoing basis" for votes on extending the program indefinitely)

110.name: a publicly accessible foreign ownership register for agricultural land
110.description: the federal government should increase transparency by creating a Foreign Ownership Register for Agricultural Land that is available for all citizens to access

111.name: addressing sea level rise as a matter of urgency
111.description: the federal government should take urgent action to address the issue of rising sea levels

112.name: speeding things along in Parliament (procedural)
112.description: Members of Parliament (MPs) and Senators should vote to speed things along by supporting motions to 'put the question' (known as 'closure' or 'gag' motions), which require Parliament to immediately vote on a question rather than debating it any further

113.name: suspending the rules to allow a vote to happen (procedural)
113.description: Members of Parliament (MPs) and Senators should vote to suspend standing and sessional orders (that is, the procedural rules of Parliament) so that their colleagues can introduce motions for Parliament to vote on even when the the procedural rules would prevent them from doing so

114.name: letting all MPs or Senators speak in Parliament (procedural)
114.description: Members of Parliament (MPs) and Senators should vote against all motions that stop an MP or Senator from speaking (that is, motions that the MP or Senator 'be no longer heard')

115.name: high speed rail on the east coast
115.description: there should be a high speed rail network connecting the major cities on the east coast of Australia

116.name: federal action on public housing
116.description: even though public housing is controlled by our state governments, the federal government should also take action to increase the availability of affordable public housing around Australia

117.name: increasing housing affordability
117.description: the federal government should take national action to increase housing affordability so that all Australians have the chance to buy their own home

118.name: ending immigration detention on Nauru
118.description: the federal government should close its Nauru Regional Processing Centre and stop all Nauru-based processing of people's claims for asylum

119.name: imprisoning immigration detention workers who record or reveal information from their work
119.description: the federal government should make it an offence punishable by imprisonment for Immigration and Border Protection employees, consultants and contractors to record or disclose information that they obtained while working in Australia's immigration detention centres

120.name: putting a time limit on immigration detention
120.description: the federal government should put a time limit on how long asylum seekers can be detained while their claims for asylum are being processed

121.name: ending immigration detention on Manus Island
121.description: the federal government should close its Manus Regional Processing Centre and stop all Manus-based processing of people's claims for asylum

122.name: protecting the Great Barrier Reef
122.description: the federal government should make laws and regulations that protect and conserve the health of the Great Barrier Reef for future generations

123.name: public transport
123.description: the federal government should increase funding for public transport within and between Australia's major urban centres and prioritise it over funding for private transport infrastructure projects

124.name: increasing the price of tobacco
124.description: the federal government should improve the health of Australians by increasing the excise and excise equivalent customs duty on tobacco

125.name: a national redress scheme for institutional abuse survivors
125.description: the federal government should create and coordinate a National Redress Scheme for Survivors of Institutional Sexual Abuse, which was recommended by the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse

126.name: strengthening gun control laws
126.description: the federal government should maintain and strengthen gun control laws and make sure they're the same around Australia

127.name: the Australian Renewable Energy Agency (ARENA)
127.description: the federal government should fund and maintain the Australian Renewable Energy Agency, or ARENA, as an independent body that manages the government's renewable energy programs

128.name: protecting citizens' privacy
128.description: the federal government should respect its citizens' right to privacy and make sure all sensitive information it does have access to (such as medical, census or tax data) is kept secure

129.name: a same-sex marriage plebiscite
129.description: the federal government should hold a plebiscite (or national vote) on the question of whether the law should be changed to allow same-sex couples to marry

130.name: lowering taxes for middle- and high-income earners
130.description: the federal government should lower the amount of income tax that middle- and high-income earners must pay each year (for example, people earning over $80,000 per year)

131.name: increasing the initial tax rate for working holiday makers to 19%
131.description: the federal government should increase the tax rate for working holiday visa holders so that they are taxed at a rate of 19% on every dollar earned up to $37,000

132.name: an Australian Building and Construction Commission (ABCC)
132.description: there should be an Australian Building and Construction Commission (ABCC) to monitor workplace relations in the building and construction industry

133.name: increasing scrutiny of unions
133.description: the federal government should increase scrutiny of unions and employer organisations by, for example, creating a commission to monitor them and applying the same standards of disclosure to them as to corporations as well as the same penalties for misconduct

134.name: stopping people who arrive by boat from ever coming to Australia
134.description: the federal government should ban people who arrive in Australia by boat and claim asylum from ever being able to apply for an Australian visa

135.name: Preventative Detention Orders (PDOs)
135.description: the police should be able to detain people without charge for up to 14 days if there is a threat of a terrorist attack or if it is likely that vital evidence will be lost after a terrorist attack takes place

136.name: increasing the passenger movement charge ('PMC')
136.description: increase the tax imposed on passengers leaving Australia (which is collected by airlines and shipping companies when passengers purchase their ticket)

137.name: more scrutiny of the Australian Defence Force
137.description: there should be more scrutiny or oversight of the actions and powers of the Australian Defence Force (ADF), both within Australia and overseas

138.name: increasing the initial tax rate for working holiday makers to 15%
138.description: the federal government should increase the tax rate for working holiday visa holders so that they are taxed at a rate of 15% on every dollar earned up to $37,000

139.name: Continuing Detention Orders (CDOs)
139.description: the federal government should introduce laws that allow people who have been convicted of certain terrorist offences to be kept in detention even after their custodial sentences have ended if there is an unacceptable risk that they will commit certain serious terrorism offences after being released

140.name: the right to protest
140.description: the federal government should protect the right of its citizens to protest against its laws, policies and decisions

141.name: increasing investment in the coal industry
141.description: the federal government should maintain or increase its investment in and support for the Australian coal industry

142.name: a Free Trade Agreement with China
142.description: the federal government should enter into a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) with China to create more favourable trading conditions between China and Australia

143.name: banning all investment in cluster munitions
143.description: the federal government should ban both direct and indirect (e.g. through parent companies) investment in cluster munitions

144.name: changing the date of Australia Day
144.description: the date of Australia Day should be changed from 26 January, which was the day the First Fleet arrived at Port Jackson, Sydney, and is a day of mourning for many Australians

145.name: doctor-initiated medical transfers for asylum seekers
145.description: the Federal Government should pass laws that ensure that people seeking asylum who are being held at offshore processing centres will be transferred to Australia for medical attention if more than one doctor say they need it, unless the Home Affairs Minister rejects it for security reasons

146.name: getting rid of the Gold Travel Pass
146.description: the federal government should get rid of the Gold Travel Pass, which gives free domestic air travel to certain former politicians, such as former Prime Ministers

147.name: changing the wording of section 18C of the Racial Discrimination Act
147.description: the federal government should change section 18C of the Racial Discrimination Act so that the words "insult", "offend", "humiliate" are replaced with the word "harass"

148.name: getting rid of Sunday and public holiday penalty rates
148.description: there should be no penalty rates when employees work on Sundays or public holidays

149.name: reducing the corporate tax rate
149.description: the federal government should reduce the corporate (or company) tax rate for all corporations (not just for small business)

150.name: the Coalition's Youth Jobs PaTH
150.description: the Government should introduced the Youth Jobs PaTH, a youth employment plan to assist up to 120,000 jobs seekers under 25 years which includes three phases three phases (skills training, voluntary internships and wage subsidies for businesses)

151.name: the Coalition's new schools funding policy ("Gonski 2.0")
151.description: the federal government should implement the Coalition's new funding policy, proposed under Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull and dubbed "Gonski 2.0", so that it replaces the previous Labor Government's Gonski agreements

152.name: technology neutral emission reduction targets
152.description: the federal government's policies to reduce Australia's greenhouse gas emissions should be "technology neutral", which means all forms of electricity generation should be on the table, including coal with carbon capture and storage and gas

153.name: requiring every native title claimant to sign land use agreements
153.description: all native title claimants need to sign an Indigenous Land Use Agreement before the Agreement can be registered by the Native Title Registrar (agreements like this let, for example, mining companies mine in an area covered by native title)

154.name: giving approval for mining in the Liverpool Plains
154.description: the federal government should give approval for new mines in the Liverpool Plains, such as the Shenhua Watermark coal mine

155.name: making sanitary items GST-free
155.description: GST should not be charged on sanitary items (such as tampons and pads) as they are health products

156.name: increasing access to medicinal cannabis products
156.description: terminally ill people should be able to access medicinal cannabis products

157.name: a Royal Commission into Violence and Abuse against People with Disability
157.description: the federal government should establish a Royal Commission to investigate and report on violence and abuse against people with disability in light of the the disproportionately high number of reports of abuse of Australians with a disability by people who are meant to care for them

158.name: criminalising "revenge porn"
158.description: the federal government should make it a criminal offence to share intimate images without consent (known colloquially as "revenge porn") and not just leave it up to the state-level governments to criminalise it separately in each State and Territory

159.name: ceremonial recognition of the first people in Australia
159.description: the federal government should support efforts to close the gap between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians by also supporting ceremonial inititiatives that aim to recognise Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples and nations

160.name: closing the gap between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians
160.description: the federal government needs to make closing the gap between Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders and other Australians a priority

161.name: maintaining or increasing defence spending
161.description: the federal government should keep up or increase the amount of money it spends on defence

162.name: Adani's proposed Carmichael coal mine in the Galilee Basin
162.description: the federal government should support the Adani Group's plans to build the Carmichael mine in Queensland's Galilee Basin

163.name: drug testing welfare recipients
163.description: the federal government should introduce mandatory drug testing for people who receive certain welfare payments

164.name: equal treatment for all couples
164.description: all couples should attract the same rights, entitlements and benefits under Australian law in both the public and private sector, whether they are de facto or married, heterosexual or homosexual

165.name: refugee family reunification
165.description: the federal government should ensure that refugees in Australia are able to apply for family reunification visas so that their families can join them in Australia

166.name: a citizenship test
166.description: people should have to pass a test before they are eligible to become Australian citizens

167.name: supporting Israel
167.description: the Australian Government should support Israel internationally and use its voting power in bodies such as the United Nations to demonstrate this support

168.name: privatising certain government services
168.description: the federal government should give the private sector control over running and managing some of its services (such as public welfare, aged care and visa services) by either outsourcing or privatisation

169.name: increasing the Medicare Levy to pay for the National Disability Insurance Scheme
169.description: the federal goverment should fund the Commonwealths contribution to the National Disability Insurance Scheme (NDIS) by increasing the Medicare Levy for all Australians

170.name: a review of our representatives' eligibility
170.description: the federal government should conduct a review of our senators and members of parliament (MPs) to make sure that they are all eligible to represent us in Parliament under the Australian Constitution

171.name: increasing federal government support for childcare
171.description: the federal government should increase financial support for childcare and early childhood eduction by, for example, supporting increased wages for workers and providing grants for not-for-profit community child care initiatives

172.name: federal government action on animal & plant extinctions
172.description: the federal government needs to support research and conservation initiatives that aim to put a stop to the current trajectory of animal and plant extinctions in Australia

173.name: increasing government funding to private bodies that provide certain services
173.description: the federal government should increase funding to private bodies that provide certain services otherwise provided by the government, such as education and health (for example, private universities)

174.name: turning back asylum boats when possible
174.description: the federal government should issue instructions for border protection forces to turn back boats carrying asylum seekers to Australia where it is safe to do so

175.name: civil celebrants having the right to refuse to marry same-sex couples
175.description: the federal government should protect the right of celebrants to refuse to marry same-sex couples if doing so would be against their religious or conscientious beliefs

176.name: universal access to abortion services
176.description: the federal government should ensure that all Australians have access to abortion services

177.name: supporting weapons manufacturing in Australia
177.description: the federal government should provide financial support for the Australian weapons manufacturing industry

178.name: expanding Medicare-funded dental care
178.description: the federal government should expand Medicare-funded dental care

179.name: increasing the Newstart Allowance rate
179.description: the federal government should increase the Newstart Allowance rate to ensure that it covers basic living costs

180.name: an inquiry into the Iraq War
180.description: the federal government should support an inquiry into Australia's involvement in the Iraq War

181.name: smaller government
181.description: the federal government should reduce the size of the public service by, for example, abolishing unnecessary Commonwealth bodies and making sure there is no overlap in the functions of existing bodies

182.name: greater control over items brought into immigration detention centres
182.description: the federal government should make laws that ensure that the minister can control what items people are allowed to bring into Australia's immigration detention centres by, for example, passing laws that allow authorised officers to search both facilities and people and seize any prohibited items found

183.name: the Paris Climate Agreement
183.description: the federal government should amend its laws and policies to meet the objectives of the Paris Climate Agreement

184.name: increasing eligibility requirements for Australian citizenship
184.description: the federal government should take a restrictive approach to granting Australian citizenship by introducing more eligibility requirements, such as applicants needing greater English language proficiency and needing to spend more time living in Australia before they can submit their applications

185.name: making more water from Murray-Darling Basin available to use
185.description: the federal government should increase water allocations from the Murray-Darling Basin for farmers and other users

186.name: privatising the ABC
186.description: the federal government should privatise the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC)

187.name: targeting foreign interference in Australia
187.description: the federal government should address the issue of foreign interference in Australia by, for example, introducing new offences against acts such as sabotage, treason and espionage

188.name: increasing penalties for breach of data
188.description: the federal government should increase penalties for breach of data by for-profit companies that have been contracted by the government to store sensitive information or to provide services to citizens

189.name: a declared area offence
189.description: the federal government should make it an offence to enter or remain in areas that have been listed as declared areas by the Minister for Foreign Affairs because of terrorist activity (such as the Mosul district in Iraq and Al-Raqqa Province in Syria)

190.name: legalising euthanasia
190.description: the federal government should support the legalisation of euthanasia (also known as assisted suicide) in all Australian states and territories

191.name: a national homelessness strategy
191.description: the federal government should work with states and territories to develop a nationwide strategy to target the increasing levels of homelessness in Australia

192.name: stopping former ministers from taking lobbying positions within five years
192.description: the federal government should tighten the ministerial code of conduct to stop former ministers from taking up lobbying positions - including in-house positions - within five years of leaving Parliament

193.name: increasing information sharing between state and federal government agencies
193.description: the federal government should work with its state and territory counterparts to ensure more effective information sharing between their agencies by, for example, storing citizens' data in central databases or creating new schemes for information exchange

194.name: promoting multiculturalism
194.description: the federal government should actively support and promote multiculturalism in Australia

195.name: increasing legal protections for LGBTI people
195.description: the federal government should increase legal protections for people who identify as LGBTI (Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender and Intersex) by, for example, getting rid of all current exemptions that permit discrimination against LGBTI people by religious insitutions (such as schools)

196.name: nuclear energy
196.description: the federal government should support nuclear energy generation in Australia

198.name: prioritising religious freedom
198.description: the federal government should protect religious freedoms over other rights and freedoms (for example, by giving religious organisations the right to discriminate)

199.name: increasing political transparency
199.description: the federal government should increase transparency requirements for political parties (for example, requiring full and prompt disclosure of any political donations on easy-to-search public websites)

200.name: a travel ban on people from certain countries
200.description: the federal government should introduce a travel ban on people from certain countries for national security reasons

201.name: MacMines' proposed China Stone coal mine in the Galilee Basin
201.description: the federal government should support MacMines' plans to build the China Stone coal mine in Queensland's Galilee Basin

202.name: a combined Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia
202.description: the federal government should unify the Federal Circuit Court of Australia and the Family Court of Australia so that they are one court  to be known as the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia

203.name: political intervention in research funding grants
203.description: the federal government should be able to intervene in the research grant process with the Australian Research Council (ARC) by, for example, vetoing certain grant application where considered appropriate

204.name: protecting Australian sovereignty in trade agreements
204.description: the federal government should ensure that Australian sovereignty always comes first when signing trade agreements so that the government can protect Australian interests (including its workforce and industries) without risking legal action from foreign investors under provisions such as investor-state dispute settlement (ISDS) clauses

205.name: targeting inequality
205.description: the federal government needs to research, develop and implement a nation-wide strategy for addressing inequality in the Australian community

206.name: pill testing
206.description: the federal government should develop and implement a pill testing policy to reduce the risk of death and/or injury caused by taking illicit drugs

207.name: legalising pepper spray
207.description: the federal government should legalise the importation of pepper spray and encourage state governments to legalise carrying pepper spray - especially by women - to deter and defend against attacks

208.name: increasing government support for the dairy industry
208.description: the federal government should increase their support of Australia's dairy industry by, for example, regulating increased milk prices

210.name: an independent ABC
210.description: the federal government should make sure that the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) is independent and free of political interference

211.name: humane treatment of asylum seekers
211.description: the federal government should ban offshore processing and not hold asylum seekers indefinitely

212.name: ending Governor-General allowances for serious misconduct
212.description: the federal government should cease paying allowances to former Governor-Generals if they are found to have engaged in serious misconduct

214.name: transgender rights
214.description: the federal government should support the rights of transgender people (including genderfluid, nonbinary and genderqueer people) by amending laws and policies to support healthy lives by, for example, ensuring that appropriate healthcare is available nationwide and that trans people are protected from discrimination and harassment

216.name: community right to say no to nuclear waste disposal sites
216.description: the federal government should be required to seek the consent of local communities before selecting new sites for radioactive waste disposal

217.name: Australia's timber industry
217.description: the federal government should protect Australia's logging industry and the jobs it represents

218.name: reducing personal income tax
218.description: the federal government should reduce personal income tax rates in Australia

219.name: increasing the Youth Allowance rate
219.description: the federal government should increase the Youth Allowance rate to ensure that it covers basic living costs

220.name: Temporary Exclusion Orders
220.description: the federal government should be able to prevent an Australian citizen aged 14 years or older who is overseas from returning to Australia for up to two years at a time for counter-terrorism reasons

221.name: making the cashless debit card program voluntary and not mandatory
221.description: the federal government should make the cashless debit card program (a program where welfare payments are put onto controlled debit cards, also known as Indue cards, for restricted use) voluntary so that people are not forced to participate in it

222.name: banning new thermal coal mines
222.description: the federal government should put a ban on new thermal coal mines opening in Australia

223.name: an independent Australian Federal Police
223.description: the federal government should ensure that the Australian Federal Police (AFP) have enough independence so that they can carry out their duties in relation to politically sensitive matters

224.name: removing import restrictions on cars
224.description: the federal government should remove the current restrictions on passenger vehicles and light commercial vehicles, including second hand cars

225.name: reducing air pollution
225.description: the federal government should develop policies and legislation that reduce air pollution, including vehicle emissions

226.name: an independent NDIS assessment process
226.description: the federal government should introduce independent assessments for access and planning decisions for the National Disability Insurance Scheme (NDIS)

227.name: investing in climate science
227.description: the federal government should invest in climate science to ensure that Australia is best equipped to deal with the challenges of climate change

228.name: building community climate change resilience
228.description: the federal government should invest in efforts to increase community resilience to extreme weather events, such as bushfires and floods

229.name: an Australian bill of rights
229.description: the government should introduce an Australian bill of rights either as a piece of legislation or as part of the Constitution

230.name: displays of national loyalty and performance of patriotism
230.description: there should be more displays of patriotism and expressions of loyalty to the nation

231.name: offshore oil mining
231.description: the federal government should support offshore petroleum mining by, for example, granting exploration and drilling licences

232.name: increasing funding for vocational education
232.description: the federal government should increase funding for the vocational education sector, which includes TAFEs, apprenticeships and traineeships

234.name: independent reviews of significant legal changes
234.description: when a bill makes a significant change to existing law, the federal government should make sure the bill includes a provision that requires an independent review to take place after a defined period to ensure that the new regime is operating as intended

235.name: increasing access to the JobKeeper Payment
235.description: the JobKeeper payment, which is part of the federal government's response to the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic, should be made available to more workers, including casual workers, workers with major charities, working-visa holders who are still in the country, and workers in sectors such as Education, Disability and Local Government

236.name: assisting the Arts sector through the coronavirus pandemic
236.description: the federal government should develop a specific Coronavirus (COVID-19) response package for the Arts and Entertainment sector as many workers in that sector are ineligible for the JobKeeper Payment

237.name: parliament continuing to meet during the COVID-19 pandemic
237.description: the federal parliament should continue to sit during the coronavirus pandemic

238.name: mandatory minimum sentences for certain offences
238.description: the federal government should include mandatory minimum sentences in their federal-level criminal laws that deal with crimes such as child sex offences

239.name: increasing support for rural and regional Australia
239.description: the federal government should increase its funding for initiatives that support rural and regional communities

240.name: paid parental leave equality for stay-at-home mums and dads
240.description: the federal government should ensure that paid parental leave provisions apply equally to both female and male primary care givers

241.name: increasing funding for public schools
241.description: the federal government should increase funding for public schools and prioritise their funding over non-government (private) schools

242.name: a nation-wide approach to border closures due to COVID-19
242.description: the federal government should encourage states and territories to stop acting independently and instead take a nation-wide approach to COVID-19 border closures through the National Cabinet

243.name: a Royal Commission into Robodebt
243.description: the federal government should establish a Royal Commission to investigate the government's Robodebt scheme, officially known as the Online Compliance Intervention, which related to automated debt recovery

244.name: banning mobiles and other devices in immigration detention
244.description: the federal government should give the Minister the power to prohibit items such as mobile phones, SIM cards and internet capable devices for people in immigration detention facilities

245.name: increasing state and territory environmental approval powers
245.description: the federal government should give greater environmental approval powers to state and territory governments by creating a single environmental assessment and approval process for nationally protected matters that is administered at state and territory level

246.name: increasing the cost of humanities degrees
246.description: the federal government should substantially increase the cost of humanities degrees at university (that is, degrees focussed on the study of human culture and society) in order to discourage students from enrolling in the the subject area and instead enrol in other subject areas, such as mathematics

247.name: reducing waste in Australia
247.description: the federal government should take steps to reduce the amount of waste being generated and exported by Australia

248.name: the Murray Darling Basin Plan
248.description: the federal government should support the full delivery of the Murray Darling Basin Plan

249.name: assisting Australians trying to return from overseas
249.description: the federal government should assist returning Australians stranded overseas due to COVID-19 by, for example, increasing the numbers of permitted arrivals under international flight caps and targetting price gauging so that return airline tickets are affordable

251.name: increasing workplace protections
251.description: the federal government should increase protections for workers by, for example, ensuring there are adequate dispute resolution processes available

253.name: extending Jobkeeper Payment
253.description: The JobKeeper payment, which is part of the federal government's response to the Coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic, should be extended for industries that are still being adversely affected by the pandemic, such as the tourism industry

255.name: increasing protections for franchisees
255.description: the federal government should amend current laws in order to address the current power disparity between franchisor and franchisee

256.name: an independent inquiry into Attorney-General Christian Porter
256.description: the federal government should establish an independent inquiry into whether Attorney-General Christian Porter is fit to remain in his role in light of the recent sexual assault allegation

257.name: a constitutionally enshrined First Nations Voice in parliament
257.description: the Constitution should be amended to include a requirement for an Indigenous Voice to federal parliament, such as that envisaged by the Uluru Statement from the Heart

258.name: implementing the recommendations of the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody
258.description: the federal government should implement all the recommendations of the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody in partnership with First Nations communities.

259.name: waiving childcare fees during lockdown
259.description: the federal government should waive childcare fees during COVID-19 related lockdowns

261.name: increasing support for the Australian film and TV industry
261.description: the federal government should increase support for the Australian film and television industry by, for example, increasing the amount of Australian programming spending required by television broadcasting organisations

262.name: supporting Medicare
262.description: the federal government should support Medicare and ensure that it is sufficiently funded to support the health of the Australian people

263.name: building dedicated quarantine facilities (COVID-19)
263.description: the federal government should build dedicated quarantine facilities in every state and territory as part of its response to the COVID-19 pandemic

264.name: treating the COVID vaccine rollout as a matter of urgency
264.description: the federal government should treat the COVID-19 vaccination as a matter of urgency and ensure that Australians are being vaccinated as fast as possible, starting with essential workers such as staff working in hospitals and aged care facilities

267.name: increasing workplace protections for women
267.description: the federal government should increase legal protections for women in the workplace, particularly in respect to sex discrimination and harassment

275.name: the Register of Members' Interests
275.description: MPs and Senators should have to disclose to the public any money they receive which could constitute, or be seen to constitute, a conflict of interest

276.name: putting welfare payments onto cashless debit cards (or indue cards) on an ongoing basis
276.description: the federal government should extend the Cashless Debit Card (or Indue) program on an ongoing basis, meaning that they should continue to put a large proportion of a person's welfare payment onto a debit card that cannot be used for alcohol or gambling and cannot be used to make cash withdrawals (see the policy "For putting welfare payments onto cashless debit cards (or indue cards) on a temporary basis as a trial" for votes on the program's trial period)

277.name: considering legislation to create a federal anti-corruption commission (procedural)
277.description: the parliament should immediately introduce and debate legislation to create a federal anti-corruption commission, or national integrity commission, that would detect, investigate and prevent corruption at a federal level (NB: this policy is related to our other policy, called "For creating a federal Anti-Corruption Commission")

278.name: Extended Supervision Orders (ESOs)
278.description: the federal government should introduce Extended Supervision Orders (ESOs) that impose conditions on a person who has been convicted of certain terrorist offences and subsequently released, if the court is satisfied that there is an unacceptable risk that the person will commit certain serious terrorism offences in the community

279.name: increasing support for the Australian shipping industry
279.description: the federal government should increase financial and regulation-based support for the Australian shipping and maritime industry to ensure its future viability and competitiveness

281.name: reproductive bodily autonomy
281.description: the federal government should ensure that Australian laws protect the reproductive bodily autonomy of women and other people capable of childbearing by, for example, protecting them from pregnancy-related discrimination and ensuring they have access to pregnancy-related healthcare services, which include affordable contraception, maternity care and abortion services

282.name: vaccinating the Australian population against COVID-19
282.description: the federal government should fund programs to ensure that everyone in Australia has access to vaccinations against COVID-19 and encourage everyone to vaccinate themselves and their families

283.name: increasing parliamentary scrutiny of bills
283.description: the parliament, particularly the Senate, should send bills to committees for inquiry to ensure that all bills are properly scrutinised before they pass through parliament to become law
